# Ledger Quest Project Rules

## Product context

Ledger Quest is a gamified bookkeeping education app for beginner business owners. Four worlds map to the 4-week course: Daily Ledger, Account Sorter, Reports Room, Year-End Boss Fight. See `docs/product-brief.md` and `docs/course-map.md`.

## Accounting accuracy (non-negotiable)

- Preserve correct double-entry bookkeeping, trial balance logic, and statement relationships.
- When unsure, check `lib/accounting/` and `docs/course-map.md` before inventing rules.
- Label educational simplifications explicitly in user-facing copy (e.g., generic sales tax model).

## Architecture

- **No accounting logic in UI components.** Components render and dispatch; logic lives in `lib/accounting/` and `lib/gamification/` as pure functions.
- **TypeScript types for all financial models** in `types/` (`Money`, `JournalEntry`, `Account`, `TrialBalance`, etc.).
- **Money in cents internally** (`amountCents: number`). Format for display only; never use floats for calculations.
- **Data via repositories** (`lib/data/`). v1 uses local storage; design for future Supabase swap without changing accounting APIs.

## Challenges & feedback

- Every challenge must include feedback explaining **why** an answer is correct or incorrect.
- Tie feedback to the learning objective; avoid "Wrong" without teaching.
- June 2024 sample transactions (Bright Path Consulting) are the primary practice dataset.

## UX

- **Mobile-first** layouts and interactions; test at 320px width.
- **Beginner-friendly** language; define jargon on first use.
- Accessible: semantic HTML, sufficient contrast, keyboard-friendly controls, non-drag alternatives for sort challenges.

## Stack

Next.js (App Router), TypeScript (strict), Tailwind CSS. Keep components small; colocate challenge UI under `components/challenges/`.

## Examples

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — logic in component
const total = lines.reduce((s, l) => s + parseFloat(l.amount), 0);

// ✅ GOOD — pure utility + typed cents
const result = sumJournalLinesCents(lines);
```

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — validation in JSX
{debit > credit && <p>Wrong</p>}

// ✅ GOOD — challenge runner uses lib + feedback model
const result = validateJournalEntry(entry);
return <FeedbackPanel result={result} />;
```
